00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:42,800
Let's just graph this function.

544
00:25:42,800 --> 00:25:44,800
We graph the function, and

545
00:25:44,800 --> 00:25:46,800
it blows up at small distances,

546
00:25:46,800 --> 00:25:50,800
and then falls off like 1 over delta squared, smoothly.

547
00:25:50,800 --> 00:25:53,800
If the particle has a mass,

548
00:25:53,800 --> 00:25:56,800
then the result is that

549
00:25:56,800 --> 00:25:59,800
the propagator falls off when delta...

550
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:03,800
becomes bigger than 1 over m.

551
00:26:03,800 --> 00:26:07,800
1 over m is the Compton wavelength of the particle,

552
00:26:07,800 --> 00:26:09,800
inverse of the mass.

553
00:26:09,800 --> 00:26:12,300
When delta gets larger than

554
00:26:12,300 --> 00:26:14,800
the inverse mass of the particle,

555
00:26:14,800 --> 00:26:17,800
the particle just has a harder time propagating

556
00:26:17,800 --> 00:26:20,800
from one point to another when it's massive.

557
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:23,800
When it's light, it can propagate a long way.

558
00:26:23,800 --> 00:26:25,300
When it's massive, it can't

559
00:26:25,300 --> 00:26:26,800
propagate so easily a long way.

560
00:26:26,800 --> 00:26:28,800
That goes back to the reason

561
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:32,800
why forces mediated by massless particles

562
00:26:32,800 --> 00:26:36,800
are longer range than forces mediated by massive particles.

563
00:26:36,800 --> 00:26:40,800
So, the typical kind of thing that happens, approximately,

564
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:42,800
this is not an exact statement,

565
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:47,800
is that you get some sort of

566
00:26:47,800 --> 00:26:51,800
thing like e to the minus delta times m,

567
00:26:51,800 --> 00:26:54,300
which gets small when delta

568
00:26:54,300 --> 00:26:56,800
is bigger than 1 over m.

569
00:26:56,800 --> 00:26:58,800
This is the kind of

570
00:26:58,800 --> 00:27:00,800
correction that comes from a mass.

571
00:27:00,800 --> 00:27:02,800
When delta is very small,

572
00:27:02,800 --> 00:27:05,800
this is not very significant.

573
00:27:05,800 --> 00:27:08,800
This is just 1 when delta is very small.

574
00:27:08,800 --> 00:27:10,800
But when delta is large,

575
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:12,800
this just gets cut off.

576
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:15,800
Now, if we really wanted to be precise,

577
00:27:15,800 --> 00:27:18,800
it doesn't really quite look exactly like this.

578
00:27:18,800 --> 00:27:20,800
This 1 over delta squared is

579
00:27:20,800 --> 00:27:22,800
not exactly 1 over delta squared.

580
00:27:22,800 --> 00:27:24,800
It's a little bit smaller than 1 over delta squared.

581
00:27:24,800 --> 00:27:26,800
In fact, it's a little bit smaller

582
00:27:26,800 --> 00:27:28,800
at every value of delta.

583
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:31,800
So, if we really were to plot it carefully,

584
00:27:31,800 --> 00:27:35,800
to plot the massless and the massive propagator,

585
00:27:35,800 --> 00:27:37,800
we would always find that the massive propagator

586
00:27:37,800 --> 00:27:39,800
was a little bit smaller.

587
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:40,800
Here's the massless propagator.

588
00:27:40,800 --> 00:27:44,800
It goes off smoothly down here.

589
00:27:44,800 --> 00:27:49,800
The massive propagator would be a little bit smaller.

590
00:27:49,800 --> 00:27:51,800
It's hard for me to draw this,

591
00:27:51,800 --> 00:27:52,800
but it would be a little bit smaller

592
00:27:52,800 --> 00:27:55,800
at all values of distance.

593
00:27:56,800 --> 00:27:59,800
So, that's one fact.

594
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:02,800
They would have the same asymptotic behavior

595
00:28:02,800 --> 00:28:04,800
near delta equals 0,

596
00:28:04,800 --> 00:28:05,800
1 over delta squared,

597
00:28:05,800 --> 00:28:07,300
but the massive one would

598
00:28:07,300 --> 00:28:08,800
always be a little bit smaller.

599
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:11,800
The propagator would always be a little bit less potent,

600
00:28:11,800 --> 00:28:12,800
so to speak.

601
00:28:12,800 --> 00:28:15,800
Okay, so that's the massless propagator.

602
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:18,800
Sorry, that's the scalar propagator.

603
00:28:18,800 --> 00:28:21,800
And I think we did talk about this.

604
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:23,800
Now I'm beginning to recall.

605
00:28:23,800 --> 00:28:26,800
We talked about a Feynman diagram

606
00:28:26,800 --> 00:28:27,800
which looks like this.

607
00:28:27,800 --> 00:28:29,800
This is one of the

608
00:28:29,800 --> 00:28:31,800
simplest Feynman diagrams you can draw.

609
00:28:31,800 --> 00:28:35,800
It represents, if you like, a correction.

610
00:28:35,800 --> 00:28:36,800
This could be a scalar particle.

611
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:39,800
Let's think about a scalar particle.

612
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:42,800
All right, this is a correction.

613
00:28:42,800 --> 00:28:44,300
This would be a correction coming

614
00:28:44,300 --> 00:28:45,800
from lambda phi to the fourth.

615
00:28:45,800 --> 00:28:49,800
Here's a vertex involving four particles,

616
00:28:49,800 --> 00:28:53,800
two in and two out, or one, two, three, four.

617
00:28:53,800 --> 00:28:56,800
And this would have weight lambda.

618
00:28:56,800 --> 00:28:59,800
Times the propagator from one

619
00:28:59,800 --> 00:29:02,800
point back to the same point.

620
00:29:02,800 --> 00:29:05,800
Now this is actually a correction

621
00:29:05,800 --> 00:29:08,800
to the mass term of the scalar field,

622
00:29:08,800 --> 00:29:09,800
the m squared phi squared.

623
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:13,800
The m squared phi squared represents a diagram

624
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:18,800
where a particle comes in and goes back out.

625
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:20,800
You absorb one and re-emit it,

626
00:29:20,800 --> 00:29:24,800
and it has a coefficient or a strength m squared,

627
00:29:24,800 --> 00:29:25,800
or m squared over two.

628
00:29:25,800 --> 00:29:26,800
That's not important.

629
00:29:26,800 --> 00:29:28,800
This is a correction to that.

630
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:33,800
It corrects the amplitude for a particle to come in

631
00:29:33,800 --> 00:29:37,800
and just go back out from a point.

632
00:29:37,800 --> 00:29:39,800
How big is that correction?

633
00:29:39,800 --> 00:29:41,800
It's just given by the Feynman diagram,

634
00:29:41,800 --> 00:29:45,800
and the Feynman diagram is lambda times the propagator

635
00:29:45,800 --> 00:29:49,800
for delta equals zero.

636
00:29:49,800 --> 00:29:52,800
So the answer is crazy.

637
00:29:52,800 --> 00:29:55,800
The answer for this process here is delta divided by,

638
00:29:55,800 --> 00:29:59,800
divided by zero squared.

639
00:29:59,800 --> 00:30:02,800
No, sorry, lambda divided by zero squared,

640
00:30:02,800 --> 00:30:04,800
or delta squared.

641
00:30:04,800 --> 00:30:06,800
And it's infinite.

642
00:30:06,800 --> 00:30:08,800
It's bad. It's infinite.

643
00:30:08,800 --> 00:30:11,300
Now we can't trust our

644
00:30:11,300 --> 00:30:13,800
theories to arbitrarily small distances.

645
00:30:13,800 --> 00:30:16,300
Presumably we expect that there's

646
00:30:16,300 --> 00:30:18,800
some kind of fuzziness in nature

647
00:30:18,800 --> 00:30:20,800
at very small distances.

648
00:30:20,800 --> 00:30:22,800
We know very little about it.

649
00:30:22,800 --> 00:30:24,800
Gravity might create it.

650
00:30:24,800 --> 00:30:26,800
Nothing else beyond what we actually

651
00:30:26,800 --> 00:30:28,800
know might create a degree of fuzziness.

652
00:30:28,800 --> 00:30:31,800
And if the fuzziness is on a scale,

653
00:30:31,800 --> 00:30:33,800
let's call it small delta.

654
00:30:33,800 --> 00:30:36,300
Let's write that big delta

655
00:30:36,300 --> 00:30:38,800
is always bigger than small delta.

656
00:30:38,800 --> 00:30:39,800
Why?

657
00:30:39,800 --> 00:30:42,800
Small delta is the smallest

658
00:30:42,800 --> 00:30:45,800
possible distances in our imagination.

659
00:30:45,800 --> 00:30:47,800
Very likely the Planck scale,

660
00:30:47,800 --> 00:30:50,800
or maybe some unification scale.

661
00:30:50,800 --> 00:30:52,800
Very likely a very large energy scale.

662
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:53,800
I'm sorry.

663
00:30:53,800 --> 00:30:55,800
A very large momentum scale.

664
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:58,800
A very, very small distance scale.

665
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:01,800
Then this O squared, this zero squared,

666
00:31:01,800 --> 00:31:04,800
would be replaced by delta squared.

667
00:31:04,800 --> 00:31:08,800
Of course if delta is much smaller

668
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:12,300
than the experimentally accessible

669
00:31:12,300 --> 00:31:15,800
things that we know about,

670
00:31:15,800 --> 00:31:18,800
and lambda is not horribly small itself,

671
00:31:18,800 --> 00:31:20,300
which it's not expected to be,

672
00:31:20,300 --> 00:31:21,800
for example, for the Higgs boson,

673
00:31:21,800 --> 00:31:23,800
then this is going to be a big deal.

674
00:31:23,800 --> 00:31:25,800
This is going to be a big thing,

675
00:31:25,800 --> 00:31:28,800
and typically bigger than the starting mass.

676
00:31:28,800 --> 00:31:30,800
So this is the problem.

677
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:32,800
The problem is you start with

678
00:31:32,800 --> 00:31:34,800
something which you imagine is relatively small.

679
00:31:34,800 --> 00:31:35,800
Small on what scale?

680
00:31:35,800 --> 00:31:38,800
Small on the scale of the cutoff.

681
00:31:38,800 --> 00:31:42,300
And then you get a correction which is far bigger than

682
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:45,800
the thing that you wanted to get out in the end.

683
00:31:45,800 --> 00:31:46,800
All right?

684
00:31:46,800 --> 00:31:50,800
So that's the problem, as we've discussed, of fine tuning.

685
00:31:50,800 --> 00:31:53,800
And another way to think about this infinity

686
00:31:53,800 --> 00:31:57,800
is to think about the proper, or the Feynman diagram,

687
00:31:57,800 --> 00:32:00,300
as being an integral over the momenta

688
00:32:00,300 --> 00:32:02,800
that can circulate in the loop here.

689
00:32:02,800 --> 00:32:05,300
You're just getting too much

690
00:32:05,300 --> 00:32:07,800
juice from very high momentum particles

691
00:32:07,800 --> 00:32:09,800
flowing around in the loop.

692
00:32:09,800 --> 00:32:11,300
So you can either think

693
00:32:11,300 --> 00:32:12,800
of a cutoff at small distances,

694
00:32:12,800 --> 00:32:14,800
or you can think of a maximum momentum.

695
00:32:14,800 --> 00:32:16,800
It comes to the same thing.

696
00:32:16,800 --> 00:32:19,800
The diagram, this is called quadratically divergent,

697
00:32:19,800 --> 00:32:23,800
which means that as the cutoff scale goes to zero,

698
00:32:23,800 --> 00:32:29,800
it diverges as two powers of one over delta.

699
00:32:29,800 --> 00:32:37,800
Okay, that's the problem for the Higgs boson.

700
00:32:37,800 --> 00:32:41,800
Now, let's discuss the propagator for fermions.

701
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:44,800
Oh, yeah, okay, let's...

702
00:32:44,800 --> 00:32:48,300
Notice that at very small distances, this e to

703
00:32:48,300 --> 00:32:51,800
the minus delta m would not help you particularly.

704
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:52,800
When delta is very...

705
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:54,800
When capital delta is very small,

706
00:32:54,800 --> 00:32:57,800
this is just approximately one,

707
00:32:57,800 --> 00:32:59,800
and so it doesn't help you very much.

708
00:32:59,800 --> 00:33:01,800
It doesn't do anything for you.

709
00:33:01,800 --> 00:33:04,800
But now let's think about fermions.

710
00:33:04,800 --> 00:33:08,800
Let's go on to fermions

711
00:33:08,800 --> 00:33:11,800
and discuss the Feynman diagrams for fermions.

712
00:33:11,800 --> 00:33:12,800
Similar pattern.

713
00:33:12,800 --> 00:33:15,300
The only difference is that the

714
00:33:15,300 --> 00:33:17,800
Lagrangian for fermions has a different structure.

715
00:33:17,800 --> 00:33:20,800
So let me write the Lagrangian for fermions.

716
00:33:20,800 --> 00:33:23,800
We've discussed it before for the Dirac equation.

717
00:33:23,800 --> 00:33:26,800
It's the Lagrangian governing the Dirac equation.

718
00:33:26,800 --> 00:33:29,800
It's actually psi-bar integral d4x again.

719
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:30,800
That's the action.

720
00:33:30,800 --> 00:33:32,800
Integral d4x.

721
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:35,300
Psi-bar, where psi-bar is just

722
00:33:35,300 --> 00:33:37,800
basically the complex conjugate of psi.

723
00:33:37,800 --> 00:33:39,800
It's the complex conjugate of psi

724
00:33:39,800 --> 00:33:41,800
times one of the gamma matrices.

725
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:42,800
Gamma matrices...

726
00:33:42,800 --> 00:33:45,800
Oh, one of the Dirac matrices.

727
00:33:45,800 --> 00:33:46,800
Psi-bar.

728
00:33:46,800 --> 00:33:49,800
And then there's a gamma mu.

729
00:33:50,800 --> 00:33:53,800
These are the Dirac matrices.

730
00:33:53,800 --> 00:33:55,800
These are the four Dirac matrices.

731
00:33:55,800 --> 00:33:57,800
They're not important to this argument.

732
00:33:57,800 --> 00:34:00,800
And there is a derivative

733
00:34:00,800 --> 00:34:03,800
with respect to x mu psi.

734
00:34:03,800 --> 00:34:06,800
There's only one derivative.

735
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:10,800
The other index is soaked up by the Dirac matrices.

736
00:34:10,800 --> 00:34:11,800
This is the structure of it.

737
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:16,800
We can also put in the m psi-bar psi.

738
00:34:16,800 --> 00:34:18,800
Notice that it's not m squared here.

739
00:34:18,800 --> 00:34:19,800
It's just m.

740
00:34:19,800 --> 00:34:20,800
Okay?

741
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:21,800
All right.

742
00:34:21,800 --> 00:34:23,800
Let's check first from this term.

743
00:34:23,800 --> 00:34:26,800
Let's check what the dimensions of psi are.

744
00:34:26,800 --> 00:34:30,800
And then knowing the dimensions of psi, we can come back to this

745
00:34:30,800 --> 00:34:34,800
term and ask whether the m that appears here really has dimensions of mass.

746
00:34:34,800 --> 00:34:36,800
We could do it the other way also,

747
00:34:36,800 --> 00:34:38,800
but let's do it from starting from here.

748
00:34:38,800 --> 00:34:39,800
All right.

749
00:34:39,800 --> 00:34:40,800
What is the dimension?

750
00:34:40,800 --> 00:34:43,800
The dimensions of an action are that it's dimensionless.

751
00:34:43,800 --> 00:34:45,800
This has to be dimensionless.

752
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:47,300
So far, I don't know

753
00:34:47,300 --> 00:34:48,800
what the dimensions of psi are.

754
00:34:48,800 --> 00:34:49,800
So I'll just call them bracket psi.

755
00:34:49,800 --> 00:34:52,300
Psi and psi-star, complex

756
00:34:52,300 --> 00:34:54,800
conjugate, have the same dimensions.

757
00:34:54,800 --> 00:34:56,800
So there's no difference in

758
00:34:56,800 --> 00:34:58,800
dimensionality between psi and psi-bar.

759
00:34:58,800 --> 00:35:00,800
So what do we have?

760
00:35:00,800 --> 00:35:06,800
We have two factors of psi, dimensions of psi squared.

761
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:10,800
And now length to the fourth.

762
00:35:10,800 --> 00:35:13,300
Gamma matrices are incidentally just

763
00:35:13,300 --> 00:35:15,800
numerical matrices, ones and zeros.

764
00:35:15,800 --> 00:35:18,800
So they don't have any dimensions at all.

765
00:35:18,800 --> 00:35:21,800
And then we have the derivative with respect to x.

766
00:35:21,800 --> 00:35:24,800
What about that?

767
00:35:24,800 --> 00:35:26,800
One inverse length.

768
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:29,800
So that's just length cubed.

769
00:35:29,800 --> 00:35:31,800
So what is the dimension of psi?

770
00:35:31,800 --> 00:35:34,300
It's not the same as

771
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:36,800
the dimension of a scalar field.

772
00:35:36,800 --> 00:35:42,300
In fact, it has dimension psi equals

773
00:35:42,300 --> 00:35:47,800
one over length to the three halves.

774
00:35:48,800 --> 00:35:50,800
Odd. Funny.

775
00:35:50,800 --> 00:35:51,800
Fractional.

776
00:35:51,800 --> 00:35:53,800
Fermions always have halves in them.

777
00:35:53,800 --> 00:35:56,800
Everything about fermions has half integers in it.

778
00:35:56,800 --> 00:35:59,800
In particular, the dimension of the fermion field

779
00:35:59,800 --> 00:36:02,800
is one over length to the three halves.

780
00:36:02,800 --> 00:36:04,800
It's a lot easier to do with the math term.

781
00:36:04,800 --> 00:36:05,800
With what?

782
00:36:05,800 --> 00:36:07,800
It's a lot easier to do with the other term.

783
00:36:07,800 --> 00:36:08,800
Yeah, it is.

784
00:36:08,800 --> 00:36:09,800
So let's do it.

785
00:36:09,800 --> 00:36:10,800
Yeah, I know, but I wanted to

786
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:11,800
show that you get the same answer.

787
00:36:11,800 --> 00:36:12,800
Right.

788
00:36:12,800 --> 00:36:14,800
All right, so let's check here.

789
00:36:14,800 --> 00:36:16,300
If psi has units of one

790
00:36:16,300 --> 00:36:17,800
over length to the three halves,

791
00:36:17,800 --> 00:36:20,800
how about psi star psi, or psi dagger psi?

792
00:36:20,800 --> 00:36:24,800
That has units of one over length cubed.

793
00:36:24,800 --> 00:36:26,800
A mass has units of one over length.

794
00:36:26,800 --> 00:36:30,800
That's altogether one over length to the fourth,

795
00:36:30,800 --> 00:36:32,800
times length to the fourth.

796
00:36:32,800 --> 00:36:34,800
That's dimensionless.

797
00:36:34,800 --> 00:36:36,300
All right, so in particular, you notice

798
00:36:36,300 --> 00:36:37,800
that what goes here is not m squared.

799
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:39,800
It's m.

800
00:36:39,800 --> 00:36:40,800
And it's true.

801
00:36:40,800 --> 00:36:43,800
It really is the mass.

802
00:36:43,800 --> 00:36:47,800
Okay, so psi has units of one over length.

803
00:36:47,800 --> 00:36:49,800
It's one over length to the three halves.

804
00:36:49,800 --> 00:36:52,800
How about the fermion propagator?

805
00:36:52,800 --> 00:36:54,800
Each one of the sides has units

806
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:56,800
of one over length to the three halves.

807
00:36:56,800 --> 00:37:01,800
And so what must the propagator be for massless particles?

808
00:37:01,800 --> 00:37:04,800
Let's start with massless particles.

809
00:37:04,800 --> 00:37:08,800
This was one over delta squared.

810
00:37:08,800 --> 00:37:14,800
One over delta cubed.

811
00:37:14,800 --> 00:37:16,800
In other words, the third power of the fermion.

812
00:37:16,800 --> 00:37:18,300
And the fourth power of the

813
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:19,800
proper distance between the two points.

814
00:37:19,800 --> 00:37:21,800
Now this is dimensional.

815
00:37:21,800 --> 00:37:23,800
Dimensional argument.

816
00:37:23,800 --> 00:37:26,800
